e and technology studies, the book explains environmentalists' success as a result of their deployment of a powerful actor-network within British Columbia's land-use decision-making process. This book makes a significant contribution to social scientific analyses of natural resource management. Bridging the gap between interpretivist and social structural analyses, it demonstrates how the Great Bear Rainforest was made -- or, rather, recreated -- out of uncertain and contested links among an improbable assemblage of actors and elements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aActor-network theory. 0aEnvironmental protectionxBritish ColumbiaxGreat Bear Rainforest. 0aEnvironmental protectionzBritish ColumbiazGreat Bear Rainforest. 0aEnvironmental sociologyzBritish ColumbiazGreat Bear Rainforest. 0aEnvironmentalismxBritish ColumbiaxGreat Bear Rainforest. 0aEnvironmentalismzBritish ColumbiazGreat Bear Rainforest. 0aEnvironmentalistsxBritish ColumbiaxGreat Bear Rainforest. 0aEnvironmentalistszBritish ColumbiazGreat Bear Rainforest. 0aNatural resourcesxSocial aspectsxBritish ColumbiaxGreat Bear Rainforest. 0aNatural resourcesxSocial aspectszBritish ColumbiazGreat Bear Rainforest. 0aNatural resourceszBritish ColumbiazGreat Bear RainforestxManagement. 0aSustainable developmentzBritish ColumbiazGreat Bear Rainforest. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aWynn, Graeme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311141999240uhttps://doi.org/1